    "source": [
      "# Phase 7 — Retrieval Augmented Generation (RAG)\n",
      "\n",
      "Until now, Claude has answered from its training knowledge. Real-world systems often need to answer from *your* documents — a knowledge base, product docs, user manuals, internal wikis. RAG does exactly that:\n",
      "\n",
      "1. **Chunk** — break your documents into small pieces\n",
      "2. **Embed** — convert each chunk into a vector (a list of numbers representing meaning)\n",
      "3. **Store** — save the vectors and original text for lookup\n",
      "4. **Retrieve** — when a user asks a question, find the most relevant chunks\n",
      "5. **Augment** — stuff the relevant chunks into the system prompt\n",
      "6. **Generate** — Claude answers based on those chunks, not just training data\n",
      "\n",
      "## What you'll learn\n",
      "1. **Vector embeddings** — what they are, why they matter\n",
      "2. **Chunking strategy** — splitting documents so retrieval makes sense\n",
      "3. **Similarity search** — finding the top-K most relevant chunks\n",
      "4. **The RAG loop** — question → retrieve → augment → generate\n",
      "5. **Prompt engineering for RAG** — how to format retrieved context so Claude uses it well\n",
      "6. **Common pitfalls** — hallucination, irrelevant context, missing information\n",
      "\n",
      "Goal: build a Q&A bot grounded in a fake company's product docs."
    ]
  },
  {
    "cell_type": "markdown",
    "metadata": {},
    "source": [
